    //
    // This partition is not valid because each class would have 'n' students,
    // and 'n' is not necessarily odd.
    //
    // However, the key insight is that to minimize the difference between medians,
    // we should try to make the medians as close as possible.
    //
    // If we sort all 2n students, the median of any class of size 2k+1
    // will be one of the elements from the sorted array.
    //
    // Consider the two "middle" elements of the entire sorted array: a_{n-1} and a_n.
    //
    // If we can form two classes such that one class's median is a_{n-1} and
    // the other class's median is a_n, then the difference would be a_n - a_{n-1}.
    //
    // Can we always achieve this?
    //
    // Let's try to construct two classes.
    // Class 1: {a_0, a_1, ..., a_{n-1}}
    // Class 2: {a_n, a_{n+1}, ..., a_{2n-1}}
    //
    // Each class has 'n' students.
