        // If loop finishes and `p_idx == m`, all tracks covered.
        // return `p_idx == m`.

        // This greedy strategy is correct.
        // The key insight is that if a head `h_i` can cover `p_j`, it should be used to cover `p_j`
        // and then extend as far right as possible.
        // If `h_i` is too far left to cover `p_j`, it cannot cover `p_j`.
        // If `h_i` is too far right to cover `p_j`, then `p_j` cannot be covered by `h_i` or any `h_k` with `k > i`.
        // This is because `h_k > h_i`, so `h_k` would be even further right.

        // Let's trace the logic for `check(T)`:
        // `p_idx` is the index of the first track that needs to be covered.
        // For each head `h[h_idx]`:
        //   If `p_idx == m`, all tracks are covered, return `true`.
        //
        //   `current_h = h[h_idx]`
        //   `first_uncovered_p = p[p_idx]`
        //
        //   // Calculate the effective range this head can cover.
        //   // The head can move to any point `x` such that `abs(x - current_h) <= T`.
        //   // From `x`, it can sweep a range of length `T - abs(x - current_h)`.
        //   // To cover `first_uncovered_p` and maximize the rightmost reach:
        //   // The head must reach `first_uncovered_p`.
        //   // Time taken to reach `first_uncovered_p`: `time_to_reach = abs(current_h - first_uncovered_p)`.
        //   // If `time_to_reach > T`, this head cannot even reach `first_uncovered_p`.
        //   // In this case, this head is useless for `first_uncovered_p`.
        //   // We need to decide if it's too far left or too far right.
        //   // If `current_h < first_uncovered_p` and `time_to_reach > T` (i.e., `current_h + T < first_uncovered_p`),
        //   // then this head is too far left. It cannot cover `first_uncovered_p`.
        //   // We should try the next head.
        //   // If `current_h > first_uncovered_p` and `time_to_reach > T` (i.e., `current_h - T > first_uncovered_p`),
        //   // then this head is too far right. It cannot cover `first_uncovered_p`.
        //   // Since `h` is sorted, all subsequent heads will be even further right.
        //   // So `first_uncovered_p` cannot be covered. Return `false`.
        //
        //   // This logic can be simplified:
        //   // If `current_h + T < first_uncovered_p`, this head is too far left. Skip it.
        //   if (current_h + T < first_uncovered_p) {
        //       continue;
        //   }
        //
        //   // If `current_h - T > first_uncovered_p`, this head is too far right.
        //   // And since `h` is sorted, all subsequent heads are even further right.
        //   // So `first_uncovered_p` cannot be covered.
        //   if (current_h - T > first_uncovered_p) {
        //       return false;
        //   }
        //
        //   // At this point, `current_h` can reach `first_uncovered_p`.
        //   // Calculate the rightmost point this head can cover.
        //   // The head moves to `first_uncovered_p`. Time taken: `abs(current_h - first_uncovered_p)`.
        //   // Remaining time for sweeping: `T - abs(current_h - first_uncovered_p)`.
        //   // The head can sweep from `first_uncovered_p` to `first_uncovered_p + remaining_time`.
        //   long long rightmost_reach = first_uncovered_p + (T - std::abs(current_h - first_uncovered_p));
